# CSS Flexbox ðŸ§˜

The Flexible Box Layout Module, makes it easier to design flexible responsive layout structure without using float or positioning.

- Good for **1-dimensional** layouts (row OR column).
- Automatically adjusts width/height to fill space.

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
}
```

# Flex Direction ðŸ§­

The `flex-direction` property defines in which direction the container wants to stack the flex items.

- `row` (default): Horizontal, left to right.
- `column`: Vertical, top to bottom.
- `row-reverse`: Horizontal, right to left.
- `column-reverse`: Vertical, bottom to top.

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
}
```

# Align Items â†•ï¸

The `align-items` property specifies the default alignment for items inside the flex container along the **cross axis** (usually vertical).

- `stretch` (default): Fill the container.
- `center`: Centered vertically.
- `flex-start`: At the top.
- `baseline`: Aligns based on text baseline.

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  height: 200px;
}
```

# Flex Wrap ðŸŒ¯

By default, flex items will all try to fit onto one line.

The `flex-wrap` property specifies whether the flex items should wrap or not.

- `nowrap` (default)
- `wrap`: Items wrap to next line if needed.
- `wrap-reverse`

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
}
```

# CSS Grid Layout â–¦

CSS Grid Layout offers a grid-based layout system, with rows and columns, making it easier to design web pages without having to use floats and positioning.

- Good for **2-dimensional** layouts (rows AND columns).

```css
.grid-container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: auto auto auto;
}
```

# Defining Tracks ðŸ›¤ï¸

We define columns and rows using `grid-template-columns` and `grid-template-rows`.

- Units: `px`, `%`, or `fr` (fraction of available space).

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr;
  /* 3 columns: middle one is twice as wide */
}
```

# Grid Gap ðŸ•³ï¸

The `gap` property (shorthand for `row-gap` and `column-gap`) defines the size of the gap between the rows/columns.

```css
.grid-container {
  display: grid;
  gap: 20px;
}
```
(Also works in Flexbox now!)

# Positioning on Grid ðŸ“

You can place an item specifically using line numbers.

```css
.item1 {
  grid-column-start: 1;
  grid-column-end: 3;
  /* Spans from line 1 to 3 (2 columns) */
}
```
Shorthand: `grid-column: 1 / 3;`

# Grid Areas ðŸ—ºï¸

You can name grid items and reference them in the template.

```css
.item1 { grid-area: header; }
.item2 { grid-area: menu; }
.item3 { grid-area: main; }
.item4 { grid-area: footer; }

.grid-container {
  grid-template-areas:
    'header header header'
    'menu main main'
    'menu footer footer';
}
```
This creates a semantic visual layout in CSS!

